<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="149" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1405,1864]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1405,1431]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Colony varies from unbranched whip to branched fans with a thick and robust axis. Polyps are densely arranged along the axis, with little coenenchyme between them. Polyps usually have a thick epidermal layer supported by collagen fibers. Sclerites in the distal portion of the polyp body are all or predominantly needles or rods with a distinctly septal arrangement. The basal part of the polyp body and coenenchyme may contain numerous scales or may be devoid of sclerites. Pharyngeal sclerites are wide, thorny rods, often with acute teeth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,626,1585,1612]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1405,1864]" box="[199,626,1585,1612]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1585,1612]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,1586,1612]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Lapointe &amp; Watling, 2022" authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[361,558,1586,1612]" class="Anthozoa" family="Keratoisididae" genus="Adinisis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="thresheri" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[361,558,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Adinisis thresheri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[566,626,1586,1612]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="149" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1405,1864]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1622,1648]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name of this genus is based on the Greek 
<emphasis box="[845,920,1622,1648]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">adinos</emphasis>
= meaning thick, dense, crowded, in reference to the very dense arrangement of polyps along the axis + 
<emphasis box="[793,830,1658,1683]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">isis</emphasis>
, the stem name of the group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="149" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1405,1864]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1694,1720]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[321,411,1694,1720]" class="Anthozoa" family="Keratoisididae" genus="Adinisis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[321,411,1694,1720]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Adinisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the thick and robust axis densely covered with generally tall polyps. This genus characterizes most of clade B1 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Watling, L. &amp; Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C." box="[606,838,1730,1756]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" pagination="337 - 375" refId="ref9546" refString="Watling, L. Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C. (2022) Towards a revision of the bamboo corals: Part 4, delineating the family Keratoisididae. Zootaxa, 5093 (3), 337 - 375. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5093.3.4" type="journal article" year="2022">Watling et al. (2022)</bibRefCitation>
(
<figureCitation box="[854,922,1730,1756]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[415,1180,182,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[393,1195,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cladogram of the Keratoisididae modified from Watling et al. (2022). New taxa added in this paper are in bold lettering. Bootstrap values&gt;50 are shown above the nodes and Bayesian probability values&gt;0.5 are shown below the nodes. Major clades are referred to by the designation along the right side of the cladogram." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877167" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877167/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), whose colony form is generally unbranched tall and curly whips, but also includes a small subclade of undescribed fan-like colonies with unusual polyps found off the Aleutian Islands, 
<collectingRegion box="[423,504,1802,1828]" country="United States of America" name="Alaska" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Alaska</collectingRegion>
. Those specimens and a large number of other species attributable to this genus will be described in a future paper.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
